image.altText: a nuclear generating station can be seen with water infront of it.

props.synopsis: Coalition promises that nuclear power will make for cheaper electricity prices don't stack up, according to an energy analyst, who says there was no evidence anywhere in the developed world to suggest new reactors were pushing down prices.

title.children: 'An absolute stretch': Dutton's promise nuclear will make for cheaper power questioned

image.altText: A black shopping basket sitting on a kitchen bench that contains bread, mince, carrots, apples and milk.

props.synopsis: Australians have few options when it comes to saving on groceries at supermarket giants Coles and Woolworths, with a new report by Choice finding a price difference of just 75 cents between the two for the same basic items.

title.children: Is Coles or Woolworths cheaper? New data shows there's only a 75-cent gap

image.altText: Two men are shaking hands and holding folders while standing in front of country flags.

props.synopsis: Vladimir Putin has visited North Korea for the first time in 24 years, signing a new partnership that one expert has described as an anti-West coalition.

title.children: Concerns for the West as Russia and North Korea sign pact to protect one another

image.altText: Coalition politicians stand on the floor of the house of representatives.

props.synopsis: The Coalition could press on "in the national interest" to establish nuclear reactors in seven communities even if locals oppose it, despite previously suggesting it would only progress nuclear on the condition that host communities approve.

title.children: Coalition backs away from plan to progress nuclear only with 'consent' of host communities

image.altText: RBA governor Michele Bullock at press conference

props.synopsis: Rate rise after rate rise should have sent the economy into a tailspin, but the RBA isn't fighting a textbook case of inflation.

title.children: What's driving our inflation? And would more rate rises fix the problems?

image.altText: A dachshund wearing a pink harness stands between a person's legs, looking to the left

props.synopsis: Pet ownership can offer a wealth of positives for many people, but for those experiencing homelessness, the costs can be insurmountable.

title.children: Poppy, Ash and Smiley all have one thing in common — alongside their owners, they are homeless

image.altText: A group of politicians in suits walk together.

props.synopsis: State premiers make themselves another hurdle for the federal Coalition to clear if it wants to introduce nuclear power plants at seven locations across the country, saying they would not cooperate to lift state-level nuclear bans.

title.children: Premiers threaten to derail proposal for seven nuclear reactors, saying Dutton has no power to lift state bans

image.altText: three women in colourful urban wear and black hijabs stand confidently against a black background.

props.synopsis: Voice of Baceprot are a devoutly Muslim all-female thrash metal band hell-bent on shattering the genre's masculine image and misconceptions about Islam.

title.children: Indonesian Muslim metal band Voice of Baceprot take peaceful brand of thrash metal to Glastonbury

image.altText: A nuclear cooling plant with a bird flying in front of it.

props.synopsis: Peter Dutton faces stiff opposition to his nuclear ambitions due to wall-to-wall Labor state governments, but figures it's simply a choice between the carrot or the stick.

title.children: Dutton's nuclear power plan relies on convincing the states, but first there's an election to win

image.altText: Giant panda Fu Ni

props.synopsis: While cuddly duo Wang Wang and Fu Ni will soon be set to return home to China, Adelaide Zoo is adamant that the pandas' love affair with the public has fulfilled predictions from prior to their arrival.

title.children: Australia's pandas may not have mated, but have enjoyed a love affair with the public

image.altText: Fleur Connick at scenic restaurant on Cat Ba Island, Vietnam.

props.synopsis: The incidence of TB in Australia is low, but experts say we must remain alert to the disease, particularly with the growing threat of drug-resistant TB. This is what you need to know.

title.children: When my GP suggested I do a blood test for tuberculosis, neither of us expected a positive result

image.altText: A composite image of a smart phone with ChatGPT on the screen and a hand holding a pen that is writing on paper.

props.synopsis: Students are central to an AI arms race in which programs generating answers for assignments and those designed to catch them out are scrambling for superiority.

title.children: Is using ChatGPT for an assignment cheating? It depends who you ask

image.altText: Rishi Sunak, wearing a suit, gestures with his hand.

props.synopsis: The date had been a closely guarded secret and the announcement took many people in Mr Sunak's governing Conservative Party by surprise.

title.children: One of Rishi Sunak's bodyguards arrested over alleged bets on UK election date

image.altText: A man in a blue morph suit controls an emu puppet in a large bush field

props.synopsis: The great emu war of 1932 is as baked into Australia lore as vegemite and chucking a sickie after a big weekend. A new film from some of our country's brightest comedy makers turns the tale into an ochre Apocalypse Now.

title.children: The Emu War is an absurd, chaotic delight featuring machine guns, puppets and Ned Kelly

image.altText: Patty Mills celebrates with the bronze medal

props.synopsis: When Patty Mills led Australia's men's basketball team to its first Olympic medal ever in Tokyo, Andrew Gaze burst into tears. The basketball legend's legacy will be front and centre again as the Boomers attempt to go back-to-back in Paris.

title.children: 'He was Superman': Basketball icon's inspiration behind Boomers' push to make more Olympic history

image.altText: An illustration of the profile of an aboriginal girl, with a red brick wall and sun in the background

props.synopsis: A coroner has made 17 recommendations to government services, saying they failed to hear the pleas of a 17-year-old to be connected to family and culture.

title.children: Coroner finds human rights breach of 17-year-old Aboriginal girl who died in state care

image.altText: A court sketch of Greg Lynn.

props.synopsis: Jurors deliberating in the murder trial of Greg Lynn over the deaths of two Victorian campers will re-watch testimony from the accused and a ballistics expert after being given approval by the judge. The jury has been considering its verdict since Monday.

title.children: Greg Lynn murder trial jurors ask to re-watch accused's time in the witness box

image.altText: A man and a woman embrace in a hospital room.

props.synopsis: After months of being held captive by Hamas, Almog Meir Jan wondered if he'd been forgotten. Then he saw himself on his guards' television.

title.children: Hamas guards told Almog that Israel didn't care about him. Then he saw his face on TV

image.altText: Joel Amartey of the Swans celebrates a goal with teammate Isaac Heeney, high-fiving and laughing

props.synopsis: Sometimes magic can take place on the football field which no-one expected. Joel Amartey produced that magic which the AFL world sat back and enjoyed.

title.children: Breaking down Joel Amartey's magical nine-goal haul

image.altText: A close up of James Marape wearing a red tie and dark blue suit at a podium infront of a crowd.

props.synopsis: Australia announces a new program to help Papua New Guinea improve its weapons management as part of a series of initiatives aimed at strengthening the country's internal security.

title.children: 'It reflects who we are to one another': Australia announces initiatives to improve PNG internal security, law and justice

image.altText: Jerry Seinfeld

props.synopsis: Footage shows security escorting a couple of people out of a Jerry Seinfeld show in Sydney. The American comedian has been vocal in his support for Israel since October 7.

title.children: Second Jerry Seinfeld Sydney show interrupted by pro-Palestinian protesters

image.altText: Professional swimmer screaming in pain after dislocating his shoulder in the pool

props.synopsis: French swimmer Rafael Fente-Damers pulled out the swim of his life to qualify for his home Olympic Games, but now he'll have to wait on the results of scans after appearing to dislocate his shoulder celebrating.

title.children: From joy to agony: How a 'crazy' French swimmer put his Olympics hopes in jeopardy by celebrating

image.altText: The outside of a modern court building in Sydney.

props.synopsis: A District Court jury has heard three women were allegedly gang-raped by three men during a bucks weekend in Newcastle.

title.children: Trio face trial accused of bucks party gang rapes

image.altText: Jacinta Allan stands in front of microphones giving an outdoor press conference. Ben Carroll stands behind her.

props.synopsis: Victorian Premier Jacinta Allan acknowledges the state's "serious and systematic" failure to protect children in government schools from abuse, while announcing a truth-telling process for survivors.

title.children: 'What should have been a happy place became a place of horror': Premier admits state's failure on school sex abuse

image.altText: Peter Dutton nuclear graphic

props.synopsis: Teased and speculated for more than two years, Peter Dutton has finally revealed his nuclear power policy.

title.children: Why has the Coalition gone nuclear? The facts you need to navigate the energy debate

image.altText: A police blockade in Melbourne's CBD

props.synopsis: A 33-year-old man has been charged with possessing explosives and making a hoax bomb threat after an incident in Melbourne's CBD on Wednesday.

title.children: Man charged, bomb squad called after Melbourne CBD lockdown

image.altText: Two nuclear power buildings in the night.

props.synopsis: The Coalition has put its cards on the table, unveiling its plan to build nuclear plants to secure Australia's energy future. But one thing was missing — what will it cost?

title.children: With battle lines drawn over who can deliver clean, cheap energy, one key question remains

image.altText: Paint on a window.

props.synopsis: Activists target the office of federal Labor MP Josh Burns overnight in the Melbourne suburb of St Kilda. It is the latest in a string of acts of vandalism linked to the Gaza conflict.

title.children: Overnight attack on Labor MP's Melbourne office 'not the way we do politics in Australia', government says

image.altText: Peter Dutton during QT

props.synopsis: Peter Dutton's nuclear energy plan is one of the riskiest gambits from opposition in many moons. He genuinely believes nuclear is the answer to Australia's energy problems, but it remains to be seen whether the details will vindicate his conviction.

title.children: Peter Dutton has placed a staggering bet on his ability to sell Australians nuclear power — it's a huge gamble

image.altText: Two investigators speaking near a police car with flashing lights.

props.synopsis: Police arrest a 31-year-old man they believe is linked to a woman's death that caused an emergency declaration that shut down parts of South Mackay.

title.children: Man arrested following manhunt after a woman was shot dead in Mackay

image.altText: Orange paint sprayed over Stonehenge

props.synopsis: The protest occurred as thousands are expected to descend on the UNESCO World Heritage Site to celebrate the summer solstice.

title.children: Climate protesters arrested after spraying Stonehenge with orange powder paint

image.altText: Dozens of hens with glossy brown feathers and red plump combs under a clear blue sky.

props.synopsis: Avian influenza has been detected at a commercial poultry farm in the Greater Sydney Basin. The affected egg farm has implemented quarantine to prevent the movement of equipment and animals.

title.children: Bird flu detected on Sydney poultry farm different to Victorian strain

image.altText: A blue and yellow sculpture of a creature playing the harmonica

props.synopsis: The small hamlet of Warrack in the Pyrenees made national headlines last year when more than a dozen of the quirky sculptures appeared on local roadsides.

title.children: World-famous minion statue allegedly stolen from small Western Victorian town

image.altText: A smiling lady in a pink hat and top waves her hands as she stands in crowd in bright sun outside Federal Parliament.

props.synopsis: Under the new arrangement announced by Chinese Premier Li Qiang, Australians will be able to travel to China for up to 15 days without the need to apply and pay for a visa, and for those looking to visit family the plan has been well received even though many details are still to emerge.

title.children: Visa-free travel for short trips to China will save Australians time and money but not everyone is happy

image.altText: Kylie dancing with a graphic saying 'how much money my online business made in a week'.

props.synopsis: Women in regional Australia are being funnelled into a multi-level marketing scheme promising a "multiple-six-figure business online" — but the "freedom" they seek comes at a cost.

title.children: Thousands of people are being funnelled into a multi-level marketing scheme promising 'financial freedom', but there's a cost
